#Clustering with K-Means
In [ ]:
#Choose Optimal k (number of clusters) using the Elbow Method
In [65]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Try different k values and calculate WCSS (Within-Cluster Sum of Squares)
wcss = []
for k in range(1, 11):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42, n_init=10)
    kmeans.fit(scaled_df)
    wcss.append(kmeans.inertia_)

# Plot the elbow curve
plt.plot(range(1, 11), wcss, marker='o')
plt.title("Elbow Method for Optimal k")
plt.xlabel("Number of Clusters (k)")
plt.ylabel("WCSS")
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()
In [ ]:
#Apply K-Means with Optimal k + Suppose the elbow is at k = 4 (just an example):
In [67]:
# Fit the model
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=4, random_state=42, n_init=10)
clusters = kmeans.fit_predict(scaled_df)

# Add the cluster labels to your original DataFrame
df['Cluster'] = clusters
